steps.body:
Memory in the Anthropic API is organized into **buckets** — named persistent stores keyed to your account. Create one for this agent:

```js
// create-bucket.js
import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";
import "dotenv/config";

const client = new Anthropic();
const bucket = await client.memory.buckets.create({
  name: "standup-agent",
  description: "Daily standup helper, single-user",
});
console.log("created bucket:", bucket.id);
```

Run it once:

```bash
node create-bucket.js
```

Note the printed bucket ID — you'll wire it into the agent in the next step.

Create `agent.js`:

```js
import Anthropic from "@anthropic-ai/sdk";
import "dotenv/config";

const client = new Anthropic();
const BUCKET_ID = "bkt_01xyz..."; // your bucket id from step 3

async function runStandup(userMessage) {
  const reply = await client.messages.create({
    model: "claude-sonnet-4-6",
    max_tokens: 1024,
    memory: { bucket_id: BUCKET_ID, mode: "read_write" },
    system: "You are a daily standup helper. Each day the user describes what they did and what they're working on. Remember it across days. When asked, summarize prior days briefly.",
    messages: [{ role: "user", content: userMessage }],
  });
  console.log(reply.content[0].text);
}

// Take the message from argv
const message = process.argv.slice(2).join(" ") || "What did I do yesterday?";
await runStandup(message);
```

The key field is `memory: { bucket_id, mode: "read_write" }` — this tells Claude to read from AND write to your bucket on every call.
